citeinfo.othercit: This CSP download dataset is in continual revision and does not represent official property boundary determinations. Park Unit and Subunit names, management status, and administrative codes are in effect beginning in the State of California Fiscal Year (YR) of release. Contact the CSP Surveys Section for official boundary information. California State Parks (CSP) is also known as the California Department of Parks and Recreation (DPR).

All products that use these data must include the following disclaimer: Disclaimer: "Parcel boundaries are approximate and should not be considered legal descriptions. Maps are intended for study purposes only."

descript.abstract: This is a GIS version of California State Park (CSP) operational boundaries and does not represent official property boundary determinations. This GIS version is intended for general reference, planning, or use in studies only. All aspects of CSP boundaries (official and unofficial) are continual revision and park unit and subunit names, classifications, management status, and administrative codes are subject to change without notice. CSP Unit and Subunit names, status, and codes are in effect beginning in the State of California Fiscal Year (FY) of release. Monitor www.parks.ca.gov for the latest information about California State Parks.
descript.purpose: California State Park System polygons for general reference and not for property boundary determination.
descript.supplinf:
The GIS version of this California State Park (CSP) polygon dataset is available for public download at the State of California Natural Resources Agency web site: http://www.atlas.ca.gov and on other State of California data portals as they become available.
California State Park System Unit names and the names of their included Subunits are tabulated below, along with their classification abbreviations and numeric, administrative codes in parentheses.
The names are official beginning in the State of California Fiscal Year of their release. CSP names, codes, and the relationships among units and subunits are subject to change without notice.
Monitor www.parks.ca.gov for the latest information about California State Parks.

attracc.attraccr: Each polygon has attributes of unique CSP Unit and Subunit names, management status, administrative codes, and system-generated (not official), approximate acreages. CSP names and codes were compiled with the best available information and are in effect beginning in the fiscal year of their release. CSP unit classifications, names, management status, and codes are subject to change without notice.

dataqual.logic: The Operational Boundary (Opbdys) is a logical construction based on parcel ownership and management information maintained by the Division (was Office) of Acquisition and Real Property Services (OARPS). In geodatabase implementation, the feature dataset Opbdys participates in a topology with the feature dataset MgmtParcels. A new feature dataset, StPrkMgmtParcels, is used to update MgmtParcels with the best available information, which is then relayed by OARPS to the Enterprise GIS Team as Land Ownership Records (LOR) in AutoCad MAP format. The publicly downloadable boundaries dataset is a commonly used subset of the above, is subject to change without notice, and does not represent official property boundary determinations.
dataqual.complete: Disclaimer: The GIS version of California State Park boundaries does not represent official boundary determinations. The polygons representing Units, Subunits, and Properties of the California State Parks System are approximate and should not be considered legal descriptions. Maps derived from the GIS version are intended for general reference, planning, or study purposes only. A quality assurance / quality control (QA/QC) report or formal completeness and accuracy assessment has not been completed on this dataset. California State Park names, codes, and management designations are in effect beginning in the State of California Fiscal Year of their release. Boundaries are in continual revision and are subject to change without notice. Consult the CSP Surveys Section for the most current boundary information. Monitor www.parks.ca.gov for the latest general information about California State Parks.

horizpa.horizpar: A formal accuracy assessment was not performed. CSP boundary horizontal accuracy is estimated to be consistent with that of 1:24000-scale USGS quads.

vertacc.vertaccr: No vertical (elevation) data are included in this dataset. California State Park elevations range from a low of 230 feet below sea level in the Salton Sea State Recreation Area (SRA), to sea-level in State Beaches (SB) and related properties, to a high of 10,804 feet on the summit of Mount San Jacinto in Mount San Jacinto State Park (SP).

procstep.procdesc: The GIS versions of CSP boundary polygons do not represent official boundary determinations. The polygons are assembled by the CSP Enterprise GIS Team from the best available sources, including CSP Surveys Section data, County Assessor parcel data, historical departmental Land Ownership Record Maps, and USGS quads in both digital and hardcopy. The CSP Enterprise GIS Team converts the source data into digital geospatial data in shapefile, enterprise geodatabase, and Google Earth KMZ formats. Selected subsets of the data are compressed into ZIP format and posted on a public download site. Download content is subject to change without notice. Monitor www.atlas.ca.gov or other State of California data portal sites for the latest version of this dataset.

The shapefile version of California State Parks boundaries is produced by dissolving one to many parcels comprising a park unit or subunit into a single, multi-part polygon record that represents combinations of park classifications and management status. See classification abbreviations in the Supplemental_Information section of this metadata.

Unit names within the California State Park System, feature class designations, and geographic coordinates were reconciled with the USGS Geographic Names Information System (http://geonames.usgs.gov). The above information is in continual revision. Monitor www.parks.ca.gov for the latest information about California State Parks.

attr.attrdef: Management Status of Park Units and Properties

edom.edomvd: Park Units are areas owned in fee title or leased from other agencies. Park Units ending with a classification type (SP, SB, SHP, etc.) have been classified by the California Parks and Recreation Commission. A unit's classification defines appropriate resource protection and use.

Distinct, non-marine areas of outstanding cultural interest established within the boundaries of other state park system units for protecting such features as sites, buildings, or zones which represent significant places or events in the flow of human experience in California.

Distinct, non-marine areas of outstanding natural or scientific significance established within the boundaries of other state park system units. The purpose of natural preserves shall be to preserve such features as rare or endangered plant and animal species and their supporting ecosystems, representative examples of plant or animal communities existing in California prior to the impact of civilization, geological features illustrative of geological processes, significant fossil occurrences or geological features of cultural or economic interest, or topographic features illustrative of representative or unique biogeographical patterns. Areas set aside as natural preserves shall be of sufficient size to allow, where possible, the natural dynamics of ecological interaction to continue without interference, and to provide, in all cases, a practicable management unit. Habitat manipulation shall be permitted only in those areas found by scientific analysis to require manipulation to preserve the species or associations that constitute the basis for the establishment of the natural preserve.

Areas where the earth and its community of life are untrammeled by man and where man himself is a visitor who does not remain. A state wilderness if further defined to mean an area of relatively undeveloped state-owned or leased lands which has retained its primeval character and influence or has been substantially restored to a near-natural appearance, without permanent improvements or human habitation, other than semi-improved campgrounds, or structures which existed at the time of classification of the area as a state wilderness and which the State Park and Recreation Commission has determined may be maintained and used in a manner compatible with the preservation of the wilderness environment, or primitive latrines, which is protected and managed so as to preserve its natural conditions, and which: a) Appears generally to have been affected primarily by the forces of nature, with the imprint of man's work substantially unnoticeable., b) Has outstanding opportunities for solitude or a primitive and unconfined type of recreation, c) consists of at least 5,000 acres of land, either by itself or in combination with contiguous areas possessing wilderness characteristics, or is of sufficient size as to make practicable its preservation and use in an unimpaired condition. D) may also contain ecological, geological, or other features of scientific, educational, scenic, or historical value. State wildernesses may be established within the boundaries of other state park system units.
edom.edomvds: Public Resources Code 5019.68 See also California Wilderness Act, Public Resources Code 5093.30 - 5093.40

edom.edomvd: Areas of State Parks, leased from the State Lands Commission, or acquired in fee, and identified as underwater park areas. The term "underwater park has long been used informally by the Department and has appeared in many publications and documents. It has, however no official (legislative or administrative) basis or standing. These underwater parks do not have specific individual names; they are an integral part of the classified units in which they are situated. In 2000, the Legislature created five new unit classifications which apply only to underwater or marine areas. It is expected that, in the future most of the State Park System's "underwater parks" will receive on of these new classifications and thereby will become individual units separate from the units of which they are now a part.
edom.edomvds: California State Parks, Planning Milestones, List 4.

edom.edomvd: Areas managed cooperatively by CSP and another entity. Examples include lands within a park unit owned by CSP or lands owned by other entities where management responsibilities and/or restrictions are shared. Other examples are road easements or rights-of-way that CSP holds on land owned by another entity, or conservation easements owned by other entities.

edom.edomv: CSP Lands Operated by Other Entities
edom.edomvd: These classified units or unclassified properties, while part of the State Park System, are not operated by California State Parks on a day-to-day basis. Local government agencies or non-profit organizations manage the units for the Department under the terms of an operating agreement or concessions contract.
edom.edomvds: California State Parks, Planning Milestones, List 10.

edom.edomv: Units and Properties that have been divested from the Department.

edom.edomvd: Units which have been designated under the Marine Life Protection Act as Marine Managed Areas, without Dept of Fish and Game Concurrence.
edom.edomvds: CSP, Planning Milestones; Public Resources Code Sections 36600 - 36900.
